The stressors that may erode resilience before the crisis include baseline anxiety, depression, substance abuse, and burnout syndrome, as well as social support system factors such as marital status, number of children and extended family.5
;
10, 11, 12 The factors that threaten psychological well-being during the crisis include the duration, anxiety about the risk of infection, financial concerns, and health system factors such as interruptions in essential supplies and chaotic communication.5
;
19
,
20 After the crisis has passed, stressors that may slow the return of normalcy include financial losses and the effects of social stigma at work and at home.5
;
10, 11 The threats to psychological health from COVID-19 can therefore be understood in a phasic model related to the advent, duration, and the departure of the crisis. These effects may not only affect the fellows and faculty in the work environment, but also the family unit that is the focus of the following section.

The psychological stress from the COVID-19 crisis may affect fellows and faculty as individuals and/or as members of a tight-knit social community in and out of the workplace.10, 11, 12
;
25 It is very helpful for the faculty and fellows to self-monitor these stressors based on an understanding of what they might be and how their effects may be expressed.5
